english:
  title: Eight Poems on Landscape Screens Presented to Minister Jeong
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I.
    Along the broken bluff a solitary boat floats in the water-village,
    Where azure grass and trees bear the fading marks of spring.
    Western winds carry the rain to heaven's edge,
    And white streaks fill the sky, dimming half the dusk.

    II.
    In the thatched hall, sitting at leisure, I cherish this quiet retreat,
    Waking from sleep, the noon-cock crows beyond my southern window.
    Suddenly the servant comes with news—
    The creek has risen and reached the bamboo grove to the west.

    III.
    Whose pavilion stands revealed on the cliff's edge?
    Tall trees and dense bamboo make one realm of seclusion.
    The low platform now sits empty, and spring grows still,
    While the master leads his guest upon a small boat.

    IV.
    Cattle come and horses go in daily confusion,
    At the official landing, boats divide the two shores.
    As the tide retreats from the sea-gate, sandbars stretch far,
    And wild geese return a thousand leagues, forming flocks of their own.

    V.
    Ancient trees and green vines reach into deepening mist,
    The monastery rises high and low, lit by silk-like clouds.
    A path at the mountain's foot connects to the peak above,
    And cloth sandals and green shoes match my wandering steps.

    VI.
    A hundred-foot bridge spans a thousand-foot torrent,
    Wind rises through ten thousand ravines; even summer stays cold.
    Where does the lonely evening traveler on his donkey return?
    His heart dwells in the hazy space between three peaks.

    VII.
    Below the fence a long river flows; behind the house, mountains rise,
    And deep within those mountains, the monastery enters the clouds.
    Waiting together for Qingming, we gather on the summit,
    Where monks and layfolk alike rejoice as one.

    VIII.
    The painting of mountains and waters flows divine and true,
    Each grass and flower blooms with its own spring.
    Yet in the end, this entire realm is nothing but illusion—
    Who knows that you and I, too, are not real?
  footnotes:
    - This sequence of eight poems praises a landscape screen belonging to Minister Jeong, blending Buddhist philosophy with literati aesthetics.
    - The final couplet invokes Buddhist and Daoist thought on the illusory nature of perception and reality.
    - Qingming (청명/清明) refers to the traditional spring festival and tomb-sweeping day.
